              paragraph:
                "Blue smoke typically indicates oil burning—common in older Volvo engines due to worn valve seals, piston rings, or turbocharger seals. White smoke suggests coolant entering the combustion chamber, often pointing to a failing head gasket or cracked cylinder head—especially in inline-six and V8 engines. Black smoke indicates a rich air-fuel mixture, usually caused by clogged air filters, leaking fuel injectors, or MAF sensor faults. Oil leaks are frequently found around the valve cover gasket, oil pan, or timing cover, particularly in high-mileage vehicles."
